nsformation and Organizational Practice -- tMoral Conversion and Mystagogy: A Franciscan Reading -- tLiberating Restoration: Ecclesial Bodies as Flywheels of Moral and Social Conversion -- tEcological Conversion as Liberation -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoral Conversion in Scripture, Self, and Society offers a broad – historical, theological, and philosophical – reflection on the phenomenon of moral conversion. Examining life-changing transformations within trajectories of spiritual and moral growth, the contributors to this volume show how individuals move, or should move, in one way or another, away from the pursuit of solipsistic satisfactions, through the practice of self-awareness and the performance of social attentiveness, toward the prioritization of shared values. Together, they address the difficulty of realizing in selves and societies some sort of definitive moral conversion – of final turn toward the truly good. Contributors are: David Couturier, Matthew Dugandzic, Erik Eynikel, Aaron Gies, Patrick Jones, Angela Knobel, Daniel Lightsey, Peter Lovas, Giulia Lovison, Krijn Pansters, Hanna Roose, Anton ten Klooster, Willem Marie Speelman, Mark Therrien, Luke Togni, Brian Treanor, Louke van Wensveen, Archibald van Wieringen, and Jamie Washam.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aKonversion. 4aMoralität. 4aSpiritualität. 4aÖkologie. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aConversion.  aEcology.  aMorality.  aSpirituality.1 aCouturier, David B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugandzic, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEynikel, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.